{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e2e849b7-7894-42aa-ab21-b4d3ea23dd4e","content":"## Connecting MCP Inspector to a C# stdio Server\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n- **Transport Type:** Select `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Args:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n  *(or just the path to a compiled DLL: `args: /path/to/YourServer.dll`)*\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Debug in the UI:**\n- **Tools tab:** Lists discovered tools; click one to invoke it with test inputs.\n- **Resources / Prompts tabs:** Browse other MCP capabilities.\n- The request/response pane shows raw JSON-RPC traffic.\n\n**Tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout only**. Log to **stderr** instead — the Inspector displays stderr in its log panel.\n- If using `launchSettings.json` or env vars, set them in the Inspector's **Environment Variables** section.\n- To attach a debugger, add a startup delay or `Debugger.Launch()` call in your server, then attach from your IDE while the Inspector keeps the process alive.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a6ebcbe3-4c25-4fb7-871e-5d0990c47b00","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"3C01:20AC41:1F5202A:2338884:69E81CD6"},"id":"8fe98995-e341-4a4c-8b47-a91f5ba1cb6e","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:57:06.001Z","parentId":"47750a0b-4bf3-40cb-b16d-425cda7a251f"}
